        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Computer-Use Models Do Differently"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A standard language model takes text in and produces text out. A computer-use model takes a screenshot image plus a task description and produces structured action commands \u2014 which element to click, what text to type, which key to press. The model must jointly solve two problems that regular language models never face: understanding arbitrary pixel images of user interfaces, and grounding natural-language intent to precise pixel coordinates."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Computer-use model: screenshot + task \u2192 action tool calls with coordinates",
          "title": "Computer-use model input/output flow"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Claude's computer-use capability is exposed through a special built-in tool named "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "computer_20251022"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". When this tool is included in the API request, Claude can respond with computer tool use blocks that specify an action (click, type, scroll, screenshot, key) and the coordinates or text content for that action."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The computer_20251022 Tool"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Anthropic defines the computer-use tool as a beta feature. Enable it by passing it in the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "tools"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " list with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "type: \"computer_20251022\""
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and declaring the screen dimensions. The model then decides when to call it and with what parameters."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import anthropic\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\nSCREEN_WIDTH  = 1280\nSCREEN_HEIGHT = 800\n\n# The computer tool declaration\nCOMPUTER_TOOL = {\n    \"type\": \"computer_20251022\",\n    \"name\": \"computer\",\n    \"display_width_px\": SCREEN_WIDTH,\n    \"display_height_px\": SCREEN_HEIGHT,\n    \"display_number\": 1,   # X11 display number; use 1 for most setups\n}\n\ndef ask_model(messages: list[dict]) -> anthropic.types.Message:\n    return client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-opus-4-8\",\n        max_tokens=1024,\n        tools=[COMPUTER_TOOL],\n        messages=messages,\n        # Required for computer use\n        betas=[\"computer-use-2024-10-22\"],\n    )"
          }
        ]
